  "text": "anchor A new installation at this year’s Festival des Architectures Vives in Montpellier draws attention to food waste through an unexpected medium: stale bread. Titled Paysage de Pain (Landscape of Bread), by MERO Studios, the project uses hundreds of recovered baguettes to form a walkable, sculptural structure within the courtyard of a historic building.The installation responds to a 2018 report by France’s Environment and Energy Management Agency (ADEME), which found that 11% of bakery bread is rejected from sale—of which 60% ends up being destroyed. In collaboration with the local nonprofit Pain Espoir, the baguettes used in Paysage de Pain were collected and reformed into an architectural system of layered curves and openings.By inviting visitors to move through and interact with the structure, the installation encourages a reconsideration of waste—not as a byproduct, but as a resource. The project aligns with the festival’s 2025 theme\" La Gourmandise,\" translating to gluttony, interpreting the concept as a lens for sustainability rather than indulgence.",
